# Dispatch for Telex ‚Äî Core Standards

## Guiding Principle

This plugin will be scrutinized by people who are skeptical of AI-assisted development and actively looking for any excuse to dismiss it as "vibe-coded garbage." Every single line of code must be production-quality, rigorously defensible, and beyond reproach. There is no such thing as "good enough for now." If it wouldn't survive a WordPress core team code review, rewrite it.

## Architecture

The plugin follows a strict 5-layer architecture. Never skip or bypass layers:

```
React UI (src/)  ‚Üí  REST API (Telex_REST)  ‚Üí  Service Layer (includes/)  ‚Üí  SDK (lib/telex-sdk/)  ‚Üí  WP HTTP Client (Telex_WP_Http_Client)
```

- The React UI only talks to the REST layer ‚Äî never calls PHP service classes directly
- Service classes never make HTTP requests directly ‚Äî always through the SDK and `Telex_WP_Http_Client`
- DTOs (`Telex_Project`, `Telex_Build_File`, `Telex_Api_Credentials`) cross layer boundaries as immutable value objects

## SDK Verification Rule

**Before implementing any feature that calls the Telex SDK, read the actual SDK source in `lib/telex-sdk/` and verify the method, parameter names, and return shape exist.** Never assume an SDK method exists based on naming conventions, documentation, or prior conversation context.

- Read the relevant resource class (e.g. `lib/telex-sdk/src/Resources/ProjectResource.php`) before calling any method on it
- If the method doesn't exist, do not invent a call to it ‚Äî raise the gap explicitly
- If the return type is undocumented, trace the HTTP response parsing to understand the actual shape before writing code that consumes it
- New features that require SDK capabilities not currently present must be noted as blocked until the SDK is updated ‚Äî do not stub or mock around a missing SDK method in production code

## Universal Non-Negotiables

- No `var_dump`, `error_log`, `print_r`, `console.log`, or `debugger` in committed code
- No commented-out code blocks
- No TODOs or FIXMEs left in committed code
- No dead code ‚Äî if it isn't used, remove it
- PHPDoc on every public method: `@param`, `@return`, `@throws`
- Imperative commit messages: "Add circuit breaker reset command", not "fixed stuff"

## Before Every Commit

```bash
make lint    # ESLint + Stylelint + PHP_CodeSniffer + PHPStan level 8 ‚Äî must pass with zero errors
make test    # PHPUnit ‚Äî must pass clean
make build   # Webpack ‚Äî must produce a clean output
```

## PHPStan

Run `make stan` (or `make lint`, which includes it) after every PHP change. Configuration is in `phpstan.neon` at level 8 with the `szepeviktor/phpstan-wordpress` extension.

Common patterns that PHPStan catches and that must be fixed ‚Äî never suppressed unless truly unavoidable:

- `fopen()` returns `resource|false` ‚Äî always guard with `if ( false === $handle )` before use
- `wp_json_encode()` returns `string|false` ‚Äî use `?: ''` fallback before passing to `md5()` or similar
- `WP_Error::get_error_code()` returns `string|int` ‚Äî widen parameter types accordingly
- WordPress filter callbacks receive `object` for transients ‚Äî use `@phpstan-var` to assert the concrete shape
- SDK method docblocks must be immediately adjacent to the method, never separated by a constant or another block
